title: 'wt shell integration / tool execution ergonomics: after ''wt switch'' or ''wt switch --create'', subsequent tool commands in this environment do not inherit the new worktree CWD because each exec is non-persistent. Investigate whether clawq can maintain/update an explicit per-session cwd across shell_exec calls, or provide safer worktree-aware affordances. Evaluate whether auto-updating cwd after wt switch is good practice versus too implicit/confusing in a stateless command-exec model.'
---

wt shell integration / tool execution ergonomics: after 'wt switch' or 'wt switch --create', subsequent tool commands in this environment do not inherit the new worktree CWD because each exec is non-persistent. Investigate whether clawq can maintain/update an explicit per-session cwd across shell_exec calls, or provide safer worktree-aware affordances. Evaluate whether auto-updating cwd after wt switch is good practice versus too implicit/confusing in a stateless command-exec model.
